  "guidedPractice": {
    "title": "Guided Practice",
    "objective": "Identify the impact on voltage drop when conductor length or material resistivity is modified in a hypothetical circuit.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Scenario: You are installing a 30-metre aluminum cable to power a motor. Aluminum has a higher resistivity than copper.",
      "Step 1: Identify the material property. Aluminum has its own specific 'Resistivity' (ρ).",
      "Step 2: Determine the total Resistance. The 30-metre length and the material's resistivity combine to create the total 'Resistance' (Ω) of the run.",
      "Step 3: Observe the effect of current flow. When the motor runs, current passes through this resistance, causing a loss of electrical pressure."
    ],
    "questionText": "Following the steps provided, explain how the properties of this 30-metre aluminum cable result in a lower voltage being measured at the motor compared to the source.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The aluminum material has a specific resistivity which, over the 30-metre length, creates a total resistance; as current flows through this resistance, it causes a voltage drop that reduces the pressure at the motor."
    ],
    "hint": "Mention resistivity, the resulting total resistance, and how current flow turns that resistance into a voltage drop."
  },
  "practice": {
    "title": "Practice",
    "objective": "Verify the learner's ability to define resistance, resistivity, and voltage drop and distinguish between them in a professional context.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Consider two cables made of the same material and cut to the same length. Cable A is very thin (small cross-sectional area), while Cable B is very thick (large cross-sectional area).",
      "Both cables have the same resistivity because they are the same material.",
      "However, their physical dimensions differ, which changes their total resistance.",
      "Voltage drop is directly affected by the total resistance of the conductor when current is flowing."
    ],
    "questionText": "Explain why Cable A (the thin cable) will cause a larger voltage drop than Cable B when the same amount of current flows through both.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Cable A has a higher resistance due to its smaller cross-sectional area, and since voltage drop is caused by current flowing through resistance, the higher resistance results in a larger voltage drop."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about how the 'thickness' of the wire changes the total resistance, and how that resistance then impacts the voltage drop."
  }
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Material Selection and Voltage Drop",
    "objective": "Synthesize the relationship between material properties (resistivity) and circuit outcomes (voltage drop) to explain why specific cables are chosen for specific runs.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Resistivity (ρ) is the inherent property of the material itself.",
      "Resistance (Ω) is the total opposition based on resistivity, length, and cross-sectional area.",
      "Voltage drop is the loss of electrical pressure as current flows through a resistance."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are selecting a cable for a long-distance run to a distribution board. Explain how the material's resistivity and the cable's cross-sectional area work together to determine the final voltage drop experienced at the board when the system is under load.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The material's resistivity (ρ) provides the baseline opposition to current, while the cross-sectional area determines how much 'pathway' is available; together with length, these define the total resistance of the cable. Since voltage drop is the loss of electrical pressure caused by current flowing through this resistance, using a material with low resistivity (like copper) and a larger cross-sectional area minimizes the total resistance, thereby reducing the voltage drop at the end of the run."
    ],
    "hint": "Connect the material's 'DNA' (resistivity) and its physical thickness to the total resistance, then explain how that resistance results in the 'pressure loss' (voltage drop) when current flows."
  }
}

